entry.title: gpu: Fix incorrect shared resource flag for D3D11 SHM GMB path
entry.content:
Do not fallthrough to D3D11 resource sharing flags when CPU read/write

is not used for SHM GMBs for any reason. Resource sharing is not always

supported on very old GPUs/drivers without D3D11 ExtendedResourceSharing

capability.



If resource sharing is really needed e.g. for WebGPU or Graphite, then

we can detect ExtendedResourceSharing and either implement a fallback

using staging texture, or downgrade the client to software rendering or

disallow WebGPU. That isn't implemented in this CL since it's a bit

involved and I'd like to keep this CL small in case of merging back to

M120/121.

entry.title: Record histograms for LCP of non-tab WebUI content
entry.content:
This CL adds some histograms to record the Time to Largest Contentful Paint of different WebUI surfaces. To achieve this, it introduces a new `PageLoadMetricsObserver` subclass that is only installed for `WebContents` associated with a `BubbleContentsWrapperT`. This should cover all of side-panel WebUI contents, as well as some bubbles set up using this wrapper.



Having these metrics aims to help analyze the performance of these non-tab WebUI surfaces, and the `PageLoadMetricsObserver` can be extended to further progress towards this goal (more metrics, trace events, etc).

entry.title: [Signin] Fix race conditions in FakeAccountManagerFacade
entry.content:
FakeAccountManagerFacade allows reading/changing the list of accounts

from different threads. Prior to this CL, it was avoiding data races

by using a lock object. However, this was still incorrect from the

behavioral point of view - it meant that calling getCoreAccountInfos

multiple times from the same method on the main thread could produce

different results, which is not how it works in production.



This CL fixes the issue by replacing the lock object with checkUiThread

and runOnUiThreadBlocking - now mAccountHolders is only accessed on

the UI thread.



Bug: 1513740, 1493636

entry.title: Store emoji picker global variant preferences
entry.content:
This CL stores the user's skin tone and gender preferences in local

storage when the flag is enabled. Individual emoji preferences are no

longer stored for emojis where the new grouped preferences apply.



New fields are also added to the existing recently-used store, to enable

users setting their global preference when selecting a variant from one

the recently used emoji. If the user has existing recently-used data,

the missing fields are filled in as emoji ordering data is loaded. There

is a very brief window after loading the emoji picker where selecting a

variant of a recently-used emoji will use the old behaviour. For future

loads this won't be an issue, because the tone and gender information is

cached in storage.



This process of filling in missing fields is potentially expensive and

happens on every load. A future CL may improve this issue by ensuring

the process only occurs once to migrate the old data. This CL would also

clean up any old individual preferences which are no longer needed.

entry.title: [BRP] Implement "same slot" mode
entry.content:
It's currently behind the bulidflag (!put_ref_count_in_previous_slot),

but the intention is to make it selectable at run-time, in order to

finch it.



Ref-count in the previous slot suffers from a race, when that slot

is freed and its MTE tag changes. Putting the ref-count in the same

slot avoids that entirely.



Ref-count in the same slot has another advantage of not sharing the

slot with the freelist pointer, so we no longer have to worry about

sizes. This CL keeps this restriction, however, as it'll make it

easier to convert it into a run-time flag.



The "same slot" mode resembles the "after allocation" mode we had prior

to crrev.com/c/2783963. The difference is that ref-count would be

placed immediately after the allocation (when raw size is known, i.e.

for direct map and single-slot spans), which added cycle to ref-count

address calculation, and created the need for ref-count relocation

on realloc.



It felt like there was an opportunity to get rid of the ref-count

table (tucked in the super page metadata area), and thus a branch

in PartitionRefCountPointer(). But there were multiple issues (see

the lengthy comment in that function), that the easiest way to work

around would be by keeping the ref-count table.
